{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523186"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13882"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.47,0.01,0.13,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6499"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2455"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30604"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe generalised pain and vomiting. She had been swimming at a beach in Far North Queensland two hours ago when she felt a minor sting on her arm. She initially dismissed it but developed worsening symptoms over the next hour. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. She has a pulse rate of 120/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is a small, barely visible mark on her right forearm. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaphylaxis","Irukandji syndrome","Acute coronary syndrome","Blue ringed octopus envenomation","Box jellyfish envenomation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003EIrukandji syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is caused by the sting of certain small box jellyfish, most notably the \u003Cem\u003ECarukia barnesi\u003C/em\u003E. The syndrome is characterised by a delay of 20-30 minutes between the initial sting and the onset of severe symptoms. The initial sting is often minor and may be barely noticeable, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey features of Irukandji syndrome include severe generalised pain (often described as a feeling that the bones are \u0027on fire\u0027), nausea and vomiting, sweating, and anxiety. Cardiovascular effects are prominent, with marked hypertension and tachycardia, as seen in this patient. The location (Far North Queensland) and the time of year (summer) are also consistent with Irukandji syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more immediate symptoms after exposure to an allergen, and would be expected to cause hypotension rather than hypertension. The absence of urticaria, angioedema, or respiratory distress also makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute coronary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the tachycardia and hypertension, but the patient\u0027s young age, lack of risk factors, and the generalised nature of the pain make this less likely. However, it\u0027s worth noting that Irukandji syndrome can cause ECG changes and elevated troponin levels due to catecholamine-induced cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlue ringed octopus envenomation\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes rapid onset of numbness around the mouth and face, followed by difficulty speaking and swallowing, and progressive paralysis. The venom contains tetrodotoxin, which blocks sodium channels. The presentation in this case, with delayed onset of pain and cardiovascular symptoms, is not consistent with blue ringed octopus envenomation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBox jellyfish envenomation\u003C/strong\u003E (specifically by \u003Cem\u003EChironex fleckeri\u003C/em\u003E) typically causes immediate, severe, localised pain and visible whip-like lesions at the sting site. It can rapidly progress to cardiovascular collapse. The delayed onset and generalised symptoms in this case are more consistent with Irukandji syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Irukandji syndrome is characterised by delayed onset of severe generalised pain, hypertension, and tachycardia following a seemingly minor jellyfish sting.","ECG changes in Irukandji syndrome may include ST segment changes and T wave inversion.","Troponin levels may be elevated in Irukandji syndrome due to catecholamine-induced cardiomyopathy."],"references":["Berling I, Isbister G. Marine envenomations. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2015;44:28-32. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/24a5a6bf-1eb6-4f50-b44b-2717c8f59b38/Marine-envenomations.aspx#:~:text=Patients%20presenting%20with%20Irukandji%2Dlike"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-08T15:23:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T09:40:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6499"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":